            <fr:title text="Boolean valuations: conjunction">Boolean valuations: conjunction</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>         The same idea comes to the fore when we look at the remaining connectives in this language.
        In each case, we'll choose how to deal with them based on their intended interpretation: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land ]]></fr:tex> as something like "and"; <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lor ]]></fr:tex> as something like "or"; <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rightarrow ]]></fr:tex> as something like "implies" or "if...then"; and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\top ]]></fr:tex> as, well, we'll get to them in a minute.
        We're working with a very simple and coarse-grained setup here, so the match might not be perfect.
        But thinking about how "and" and "or" and "if...then" work can get us some way along the path to seeing what we're doing with these connectives, just like thinking about "not" can help with understanding <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg ]]></fr:tex>.
        Here's how Boolean valuations deal with conjunctions: a conjunction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \land  B]]></fr:tex> gets the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> on a given valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> exactly when <html:em>both</html:em> of its components <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> get value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> on the valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>.
        Otherwise, the conjunction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \land  B]]></fr:tex> gets the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>         Why deal with conjunction this way?
        Think, for example, about the claim "The moon is made of green cheese, and Carl is a good dog".
        Is this claim true or false?
        Well, "the moon is made of green cheese" is false, and "Carl is a good dog" is true.
        So if someone said to us "the moon is made of green cheese and Carl is a good dog", then what they've said is false: the falsity of the first part undermines the whole claim.
        They in effect said that both of these were true, and that's not so; so what they've said is false.
        This is why, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land ]]></fr:tex>, we go with a setup that requires both components to be true on a valuation for the conjunction itself to be true on that valuation.
        Just as with negation, we can record this information in a table:            
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://www.my-great-forest.net/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>21</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://www.my-great-forest.net/003K/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>003K</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/003K/</fr:route>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:table style="border-collapse: collapse;">
  <html:thead><html:tr>
    <html:td class="topedge leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land ]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  </html:tr></html:thead>
  <html:tbody>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
  </html:tbody>
</html:table>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>Since this table is for a binary connective rather than a unary one, we read it slightly differently from the table for negation.
Let's say you want to use this table to calculate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p \land  q)]]></fr:tex> on some valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w]]></fr:tex> where you know that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>.
        Use the left component of the conjunction to choose a row of the table, by finding the appropriate value along the left edge.
        In this case, the left component is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, so you choose the bottom row of the table.
        Then, use the right component of the conjunction to choose a column of the table, by finding the appropriate value along the top edge.
        In this case, the right component is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, so you choose the column headed by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>.
        By finding the entry where this row and column meet, you find the value your conjunction must take; in this case, this tells us that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p \land  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
        As with negation, you might find that you don't need the table for long, that it's enough to remember that both components must be true for the conjunction to be true.
        But as with negation, we're going to see more complex alternatives in a moment, so it's good to be able to read these tables.
</html:p>
            <html:p>         The value of a negation or a conjunction, in a Boolean valuation, depends only on the values of its component(s).
        This is so even when the components are themselves compound sentences.
        So, for example, consider a valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p) = v(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>; you now know enough to calculate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg (p \land  \neg  q))]]></fr:tex>.
        Do it step by step: first <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p \land  \neg  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, and finally <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg (p \land  \neg  q)) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>.
        So once you know the Boolean tables for each connective, you will be able to calculate the value of any formula on any Boolean valuation, no matter how complex the formula is, so long as you know the values of the atomic formulas it contains.
</html:p>
